<section xml:id="section-activity-clo9">
  <title>Activity for CLO-9</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo9-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a continuous function.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It is a function whose graph can be drawn with an
          uninterupted path. More formally, a function is continuous
          at a point <m>a</m> if the following equation holds. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow a} f(x) = f(a)
          </md>
          This says that the limit, the process of approaching, is
          the same as the actual value of the function. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does it mean for a function to be <sq>continuous on its
          domain</sq>? Which functions have this property?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A function is continuous on its domain its graph can be
          drawn with a single path other than breaks in the domain.
          Equivalently, the limit definition of continuity holds for
          all points in the domain. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the intermediate value theorem?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The intermediate value theory is a fancy theory that makes a
          pretty simple point: if a contuous function has two outputs
          which are different, then it must go through all
          intermediate output. In terms of position, if a continuous
          function measure the travel from point A to point B, it also
          has to pass through all points in-between. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a piecewise function? Why is continuity of
          particular concern for these functions?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A piecewise function is a function which has a different
          definition at different points in its domain. Between the
          different sections, there are often cross-over point where
          the definition changes. These are important points for
          continuity: we want to know whether the two different
          definitions of the function actually match up with each
          other at the cross-over point. If they do and they form a
          connected path, the function is continuous at that point. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How do you test the continuity of a piecewise function at a
          cross-over point?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          You take the limit from both sides. If both limits exist and
          both are equal to the actualy function value at that point,
          then the function is continuous at the cross-over point. 
        </p>
        <p>
          It is important that a limit is used. I am not evaluating
          both peicese at the cross-over point, I am taking the limit
          approaching the cross-over point. If both limits can be
          directly evaluated, it may feel like just evaluating, but
          using a limit is an important conceptual piece that should
          not be forgotten. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-conintuity">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Continuity</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a value for <m>a</m> (if there is any) which makes this
          piecewise function continuous.
          <md>
            f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix}
            x+3 \amp x > 0 \\
            -2x + a \amp x \leq 0 
            \end {matrix} \right.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine continuity, I need to take the limit from the
          left and the limit from the right approaching the cross over
          point. Here are the two limits, both of which can be
          evaluated directly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^+} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^+} x+3 = 3 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-} -2x + a = a 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Making these equal gives the equation
          <md>
            3 = a 
          </md>.
          This equation is (obviously) solved when <m>a=3</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a value for <m>a</m> (if there is any) which makes this
          piecewise function continuous.
          <md>
            f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix}
            x^2 + 2x + 5 \amp x \lt -1 \\
            ax^2 \amp x \geq -1 
            \end {matrix} \right.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine continuity, I need to take the limit from the
          left and the limit from the right approaching the cross over
          point. Here are the two limits, both of which can be
          evaluated directly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow -1^+} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow -1^+} ax^2 = a
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow -1^-} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow -1^-} x^2 + 2x + 5 = 1 - 2 + 5 = 4
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Making these equal gives the equation
          <md>
            a = 4 
          </md>.
          This equation is (obviously) solved when <m>a = 4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a value for <m>a</m> (if there is any) which makes this
          piecewise function continuous.
          <md>
            f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix}
            \sin (\pi x)  \amp x > \frac{5}{2} \\
            x^2 + ax + 2  \amp x \leq \frac{5}{2}
            \end {matrix} \right.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine continuity, I need to take the limit from the
          left and the limit from the right approaching the cross over
          point. Here are the two limits, both of which can be
          evaluated directly. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{5}{2}^+} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{5}{2}^+} \sin (\pi x) = \sin
              \left( \frac{5\pi}{2} \right) = 1 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{5}{2}^-} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{5}{2}^-} x^2 + ax + 2 =
              \frac{25}{4} + \frac{5a}{2} + 2  = \frac{33 + 10a}{4} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Making these equal gives the equation
          <md>
            1 = \frac{33 + 10a}{4} 
          </md>
          This equation is solved when <m>a = \frac{-29}{10}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find a value for <m>a</m> (if there is any) which makes this
          piecewise function continuous.
          <md>
            f(x) = \left\{ \begin{matrix}
            \frac{1}{x} \amp x > 0 \\
            x^2 + ax + a \amp x \leq 0 
            \end {matrix} \right.
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To determine continuity, I need to take the limit from the
          left and the limit from the right approaching the cross over
          point. Here are the two limits. The second can be evaluated
          directly, and the first diverges by logical analysis of the
          pieces. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^+} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^+} \frac{1}{x} = \infty 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-} f(x) \amp = 
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0^-} x^2 + ax + a = a
            </mrow>
          </md>
          I cannot equate these limits, since <m>\infty</m> is not a
          number. There is no value of <m>a</m> which makes this
          piecewise function continuous. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
